[
    {
        "content": "<p>In the context of cohesive topoi, we speak of the three functors: flat, shape, and sharp. In particular, only the first two play an important role in the definition of the differential cohomology hexagon. How does one understand concretely the sharp modality and its uses? Are there some notable examples of images under it? I am particularly curious whether the hexagon further extends by considering how flat and sharp interact as adjoints/</p>",
        "id": 595876383,
        "sender_full_name": "Alonso Perez-Lona",
        "timestamp": 1779122527
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For some context: <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/differential+cohomology+diagram\">[[differential cohomology diagram]]</a></p>",
        "id": 595901585,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1779128980
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here are a conceptual and practical POV on the sharp modality.</p>",
        "id": 595901586,
        "sender_full_name": "Adrian Clough",
        "timestamp": 1779128980
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Conceptually, the sharp modality tells you that your topos (let's call it <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0894em;\">E</span></span></span></span>) has a final object when viewed as on object in the 2-category of toposes, i.e., the unique geometric morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E} \\to \\mathcal{S}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0894em;\">E</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span> to the topos of sets / anima admits a right adjoint. (Note that in the 2-category of categories, a category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0715em;\">C</span></span></span></span> has a final object iff the unique morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>→</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C \\to 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0715em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> has a right adjoint). This essentially tells you that the final object (in usual sense) in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0894em;\">E</span></span></span></span> geometrically looks like a point.</p>",
        "id": 595904633,
        "sender_full_name": "Adrian Clough",
        "timestamp": 1779129340
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Practically, the sharp modality allows you to define concrete objects as objects <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span></span></span></span> in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0894em;\">E</span></span></span></span> for which the canonical morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to \\sharp X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is a monomorphism. This makes it fairly easy for example to prove that that the category of concrete objects in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0894em;\">E</span></span></span></span> is presentable.</p>",
        "id": 595905633,
        "sender_full_name": "Adrian Clough",
        "timestamp": 1779129469
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't know how <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\sharp</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span></span></span></span> interacts with differential cohomology.</p>",
        "id": 595906479,
        "sender_full_name": "Adrian Clough",
        "timestamp": 1779129568
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277917\">Adrian Clough</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/411257-theory.3A-mathematics/topic/Concrete.20use.20of.20the.20sharp.20modality/near/595905633\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Practically, the sharp modality allows you to define concrete objects as objects <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span></span></span></span> in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0894em;\">E</span></span></span></span> for which the canonical morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to \\sharp X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is a monomorphism.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Thanks, Adrian. So for example, in the case <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to \\sharp X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is a monomorphism, how to understand the \"extra\" information in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\sharp X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span></span></span></span>? For instance, how to understand the morphisms <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> for which there is a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\sharp X \\to Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> closing the triangle?</p>",
        "id": 595910978,
        "sender_full_name": "Alonso Perez-Lona",
        "timestamp": 1779130331
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's a way to understand the difference between <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/intensive+or+extensive+quantity#in_modal_homotopy_type_theory\">intensive and extensive quantities</a> via <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\sharp</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 595916123,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1779131724
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"565212\">Alonso Perez-Lona</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/411257-theory.3A-mathematics/topic/Concrete.20use.20of.20the.20sharp.20modality/near/595910978\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Thanks, Adrian. So for example, in the case <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to \\sharp X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is a monomorphism, how to understand the \"extra\" information in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\sharp X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span></span></span></span>? For instance, how to understand the morphisms <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> for which there is a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\sharp X \\to Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> closing the triangle?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I don't have a particularly sophisticated view on what <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\sharp</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span></span></span></span> does to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span></span></span></span>. If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is a manifold in the cohesive topos of sheaves on manifolds, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\sharp X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is essentially the underlying set of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span></span></span></span> with the trivial topology. I guess a morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> factoring as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to \\sharp X \\to Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> just means that the image of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> has the trivial topology in some sense.</p>",
        "id": 595918160,
        "sender_full_name": "Adrian Clough",
        "timestamp": 1779132304
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"302507\">David Corfield</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/411257-theory.3A-mathematics/topic/Concrete.20use.20of.20the.20sharp.20modality/near/595916123\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>There's a way to understand the difference between <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/intensive+or+extensive+quantity#in_modal_homotopy_type_theory\">intensive and extensive quantities</a> via <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">♯</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\sharp</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">♯</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I see, this and the perspective in terms of generalized homology in the same nLab page is very helpful, thanks!</p>",
        "id": 595920333,
        "sender_full_name": "Alonso Perez-Lona",
        "timestamp": 1779133009
    }
]